ce:section.ce:para:
The practical utility of CQDs was explored in detecting AB in human urine samples obtained from various individuals. CQDs detect AB in urine based on their luminous characteristics and strong interactions with AB. Upon treatment with human urine samples, the fluorescence emission intensity of CQDs remained consistent with that of AB-spiked samples. In the absence of AB, the fluorescence intensity of CQDs exhibited a slight quenching effect (14 %) in the bare urine solution. However, upon spiking AB (3.3 µM) into the urine solution, an additional 23 % quenching in fluorescence intensity was observed (Fig. 7
                     ). The AB interacts with CQDs via non-covalent forces, particularly hydrogen bonding, which disturbs energy transfer processes and affects electronic transitions, resulting in fluorescence quenching. The porosity and multifunctional sites of CQDs facilitate these interactions, allowing for efficient charge and energy transfer [53]. The analysis presented in Table 2
                      delineates the diverse recovery percentages and mean standard deviations across different human urine samples. Remarkably, a substantial recovery percentage of AB (ranging from 81 % to 123 %) was achieved from the human urine samples utilizing this method. These results underscore the outstanding accuracy, recovery, and potential of the proposed approach for detecting AB in real samples.
